<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911022-0079</DOCNO><DOCID>911022-0079.</DOCID><HL>   Letters to the Editor:   There's No Ignoring   Asbestos-Removal Rule</HL><DATE>10/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A21</SO><CO>   LABOR</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)INDUSTRIAL (IDU)</MS><IN>BUILDING MATERIALS, CONCRETE, GLASS, PAINT (BLD)REAL ESTATE INVESTMENTS (REA)</IN><NS>LABOR, UNIONS, STRIKES, WAGES, RECRUITMENT (LAB)</NS><GV>ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (EPA)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   Your coverage of the Health Effects Institute's report onasbestos (Sept. 25) may mislead your readers into thinkingthat we can ignore asbestos now.   The important fact overlooked is that, ultimately, theEnvironmental Protection Agency requires that asbestos mustbe removed before renovation or demolition that would disturbfibers. The real issue then is: Remove now or remove later?Each building manager should respond to this report byensuring that his building is &quot;well-maintained&quot; to avoidexposure to fibers that remain potentially deadly. Thisrequires proper training, education and supervision.</LP><TEXT>   Thousands of facility owners are already doing just that,taking the proper steps to have their workers, tenants andoutside contractors protected.   William D. Scott   President   National Asbestos Council Inc.   Atlanta</TEXT></DOC>